&gt; Hi Jeff, 
&gt; 
&gt; I guess such bloat is inevitable in case of fitness plateau being reached. One
&gt; suggestion is to try pruning the networks with the addition of subtractive
&gt; mutations (remove link & remove node). Or better try phased searching,
&gt; complexification followed by simplification stages. This will improve things
&gt; for sure. 
&gt; 
&gt; Peter
&gt; 
&gt; --- In neat@yahoogroups.com, Jeff Clune &lt;jclune@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; Hello all-
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; I have been noticing in many of my HyperNEAT runs recently that the number
&gt;&gt; of CPPN nodes is shooting up as a steep linear function of time
&gt;&gt; (generations), and is relatively unaffected by the fitness trajectory of the
&gt;&gt; run. 
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; See here, for example
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; https://www.msu.edu/~jclune/delme/CPPN-Node-Bloat-1.png
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; Sometimes it gets really pathological, with almost 25 CPPN nodes being added
&gt;&gt; every 100 generations, such as here:
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; https://www.msu.edu/~jclune/delme/CPPN-Node-Bloat-2.png
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; Oddly, and interestingly, the runs in this second figure where the CPPN node
&gt;&gt; count linearly increases are in a changing environment and those runs where
&gt;&gt; the CPPN node count flatlines (at a healthy level) are in a constant
&gt;&gt; environment.
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; Are any of you seeing such bloat?
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; One problem is that it makes the runs slow to a crawl, because running
&gt;&gt; populations with 200-node genomes is really slow. Moreover, I doubt
&gt;&gt; evolution can make too much progress with that many nodes (although I have
&gt;&gt; seen fitness continue to increase even with such large genomes).
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; I have tried dropping the MutateAddNodeProbability from 0.03 to 0.003 and
&gt;&gt; that definitely changes the slope of the line, but it still linearly
&gt;&gt; increases. The good news is that it does not affect fitness to much.
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; Any thoughts? 
&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt; 
